    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1975-07-31T08:25:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1975-07-31T06:25:00-05:00" n="331"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d331">
                <head>331. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d331fn1"
                        >Source: Ford Library, National Security Adviser, Memoranda of Conversation,
                        Box 14. Secret. Drafted by Obst. The conversation took place at the
                        Residence of the British Ambassador.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Helsinki</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1975-07-31T13:25:00+02:00" to="1975-07-31T15:25:00+02:00"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date">July 31, 1975, 1:25–3:25 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECTS</head>
                    <item>President <persName corresp="#p_KU1">Kekkonen</persName>’s Dinner</item>
                    <item>Reaction to <persName corresp="#p_BLI1">Brezhnev</persName>’s Speech at
                            <gloss target="#t_CSCE1">CSCE</gloss> Summit</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BLI1">Brezhnev</persName>’s Health</item>
                    <item>The Middle East</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_UK1">
                            <hi rend="italic">UK</hi>
                        </gloss>
                        <list>
                            <item>Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_WJH2">Wilson</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs <persName corresp="#p_CLJ1"
                                    >Callaghan</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <pb facs="1003" n="968" xml:id="pg_968"/>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">France</hi>
                        <list>
                            <item>President <persName corresp="#p_GdEV1">Giscard
                                    d’Estaing</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Minister of Foreign Affairs Sauvagnargues</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_FRG1">
                            <hi rend="italic">FRG</hi>
                        </gloss>
                        <list>
                            <item>Chancellor Schmidt</item>
                            <item>Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_GHD1">Genscher</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Gisela Anders, Interpreter</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>
                        <list>
                            <item>President Ford</item>
                            <item>Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                                    >Kissinger</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>
                                <persName>Harry Obst</persName>, interpreter</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>(These excerpts refer only to the first hour of conversation at the lunch table.
                    The remainder of the conversation, held in the garden, discussing the pre-agreed
                    agenda was held by the eight participants only without the presence of
                    interpreters or notetakers.)</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName corresp="#p_KU1">Kekkonen</persName>’s
                        Dinner</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Both the President and Chancellor <persName corresp="#p_SH1">Schmidt</persName>
                    complained about the unfortunate seating arrangement at the dinner and in the
                    plenary of the <gloss target="#t_CSCE1">CSCE</gloss>. President <persName
                        corresp="#p_FGR1">Ford</persName> remarked that he spent virtually all his
                    time talking to <persName corresp="#p_HE2">Erich Honecker</persName> and
                    Archbishop <persName corresp="#p_MIII1">Makarios</persName>. Chancellor
                        <persName corresp="#p_SH1">Schmidt</persName> also complained about his
                    delegation being seated next to the <gloss target="#t_GDR1">GDR</gloss> which
                    left him no choice but to converse with Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HE2"
                        >Honecker</persName>. Secretary <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                        >Kissinger</persName> commented that the long talk <persName
                        corresp="#p_MIII1">Makarios</persName> had with the President was ironic
                    inasmuch as the United States Government had not previously agreed to a meeting
                    between the two.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Reaction to <persName corresp="#p_BLI1">Brezhnev</persName>’s
                        Speech at <gloss target="#t_CSCE1">CSCE</gloss> Summit</hi>
                </p>
                <p>President <persName corresp="#p_GdEV1">Giscard</persName> asked the participants
                    about their reaction to today’s (July 31) speech of <persName corresp="#p_BLI1"
                        >Leonid Brezhnev</persName>.<note n="2" xml:id="d331fn2">For the text of
                            <persName corresp="#p_BLI1">Brezhnev</persName>’s speech, see Current
                        Digest of the Soviet Press, <gloss target="#t_Vol1">Vol.</gloss> XXVII:22
                        (August 27, 1975), pp. 6–7.</note> President <persName corresp="#p_FGR1"
                        >Ford</persName> commented that he had found it very interesting inasmuch as
                    it had been restrained and very moderate in its statements. At any rate, it
                    definitely had been quite different from what it could have been. Chancellor
                        <persName corresp="#p_SH1">Schmidt</persName> agreed. He said that there had
                    been no “stings” in the speech and that it had been more moderate than that of
                    Gierek. Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_WJH2">Wilson</persName> said that
                    he was surprised that the speech actually contained some reference to actions
                    based on the Helsinki documents. Secretary <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                        >Kissinger</persName> said that <persName corresp="#p_BLI1"
                        >Brezhnev</persName>’s statements on “no interference” had been read by some
                    as meaning that he was ready to bury the <persName corresp="#p_BLI1"
                        >Brezhnev</persName> Doctrine.</p>
                <pb facs="1004" n="969" xml:id="pg_969"/>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Brezhnev’s Health</hi>
                </p>
                <p>When the question of <persName corresp="#p_BLI1">Brezhnev</persName>’s health was
                    raised, President Ford commented that <persName corresp="#p_BLI1"
                        >Brezhnev</persName> had clearly seemed very tired at the end of the very
                    long sessions he had had with him in Vladivostok. Prime Minister <persName
                        corresp="#p_WJH2">Wilson</persName> said that he definitely thought that
                        <persName corresp="#p_BLI1">Brezhnev</persName> was looking much better than
                    when he had seen him in Moscow in February.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion of matters other than the European security
                    conference or <gloss target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss>.]</p>
            </div>
